(children laugh)

00:33:03.114 --> 00:33:04.449
Heckman:
Childcare can't be

00:33:04.449 --> 00:33:05.950
some kind of warehouse,

00:33:05.950 --> 00:33:09.787
because it's more than
just taking care of the child

00:33:09.787 --> 00:33:11.022
for eight hours a day.

00:33:11.022 --> 00:33:12.623
I need to find a wig for that.

00:33:12.623 --> 00:33:14.359
Should I wear a curly wig?

00:33:14.359 --> 00:33:15.860
Heckman:
Quality early childhood program

00:33:15.860 --> 00:33:18.463
is an opportunity to invest
in the child

00:33:18.463 --> 00:33:20.498
and to promote
the capabilities of the child.

00:33:20.498 --> 00:33:22.133
Woman:
Who are you?

00:33:22.133 --> 00:33:23.668
Fireman!

00:33:23.668 --> 00:33:25.370
Narrator:
Studies by Heckman, Art Rolnick,

00:33:25.370 --> 00:33:27.205
and others show that children

00:33:27.205 --> 00:33:31.209
who receive high quality care
are on average better educated,

00:33:31.209 --> 00:33:34.779
healthier, more productive,
and earn higher pay...

00:33:34.779 --> 00:33:36.314
Fire! Fire!

00:33:36.314 --> 00:33:38.282
Oh, where is there a fire?

00:33:38.282 --> 00:33:40.184
Way over there!

00:33:40.184 --> 00:33:41.452
Narrator:
...While lowering the cost

00:33:41.452 --> 00:33:45.456
to society of unemployment,
social services, health care,

00:33:45.456 --> 00:33:47.458
and incarceration.

00:33:47.458 --> 00:33:48.826
Heckman:
These kids actually have

00:33:48.826 --> 00:33:50.728
what economists call
a rate of return.

00:33:50.728 --> 00:33:55.733
For each dollar invested,
you get back 7% to 10%,

00:33:55.733 --> 00:33:58.870
somewhere between 7%
and 10% per annum

00:33:58.870 --> 00:34:00.538
over the lifetime of the child.

00:34:00.538 --> 00:34:03.307
Which is a huge rate of return.

00:34:03.307 --> 00:34:05.643
In the US stock market,
a good portfolio,

00:34:05.643 --> 00:34:10.048
an average portfolio
would earn about 6% a year.

00:34:10.048 --> 00:34:13.651
if you were a financial
planner, investor,

00:34:13.651 --> 00:34:15.987
or if you were a government
or somebody asking,

00:34:15.987 --> 00:34:17.522
"Where should I put my money?

00:34:17.522 --> 00:34:19.991
In the stock market
or in a young child?"

00:34:19.991 --> 00:34:22.790
You'd say in a young child.

00:34:23.928 --> 00:34:25.530
Narrator:
But that's not where the nation

00:34:25.530 --> 00:34:27.165
is investing.

00:34:27.165 --> 00:34:28.499
Across the country,

00:34:28.499 --> 00:34:33.438
only one in 10 childcare centers
is accredited.

00:34:33.438 --> 00:34:34.705
n California,

00:34:34.705 --> 00:34:38.164
cemeteries are inspected more
often than childcare centers.

00:34:39.544 --> 00:34:43.742
Staff training is often not
required and oversight is lax.

00:34:45.683 --> 00:34:49.020
The annual median wage
for American's childcare workers

00:34:49.020 --> 00:34:53.891
in 2013 was only $19,600-

00:34:53.891 --> 00:34:56.724
less than poverty level
for a family of three.

00:34:57.929 --> 00:34:59.920
Are your dinosaurs
joining us?

00:35:01.532 --> 00:35:03.234
Yaminette:
The backup plan is

00:35:03.234 --> 00:35:04.497
to get into Ellis.

00:35:06.037 --> 00:35:08.973
And if, come September,
that doesn't work out,

00:35:08.973 --> 00:35:12.102
then David and I will figure
something else out...

00:35:12.810 --> 00:35:14.445
Stack 'em up for her.

00:35:14.445 --> 00:35:15.279
One, two...

00:35:15.279 --> 00:35:17.248
Narrator:
Yaminette and David,

00:35:17.248 --> 00:35:19.383
and millions
of American parents,

00:35:19.383 --> 00:35:22.220
would not have to
“figure something else out”

00:35:22.220 --> 00:35:23.821
if the nation had done

00:35:23.821 --> 00:35:27.883
what it was on the verge
of doing almost 45 years ago.

00:35:29.327 --> 00:35:33.297
Back in 1971,
Congress passed legislation

00:35:33.297 --> 00:35:37.568
called the Comprehensive Child
Development Act or CCDA.

00:35:37.568 --> 00:35:41.339
It offered universal, high
quality childcare, preschool,

00:35:41.339 --> 00:35:45.009
and other services for children
from birth to age five

00:35:45.009 --> 00:35:48.468
to any and every American
family that wanted them.

00:35:50.414 --> 00:35:53.484
The legislation awaited
only a presidential signature

00:35:53.484 --> 00:35:54.815
to become law.

00:35:55.653 --> 00:35:57.155
Reporter:
The word is now

00:35:57.155 --> 00:35:58.689
that the Administration
will announce

00:35:58.689 --> 00:36:00.358
its position next week.

00:36:00.358 --> 00:36:03.919
And the day of daycare may
be approaching in America.

00:36:06.264 --> 00:36:08.166
Narrator:
But opponents recast the bill

00:36:08.166 --> 00:36:09.834
as government intrusion

00:36:09.834 --> 00:36:14.066
into the individual rights and
responsibilities of the family.

00:36:15.673 --> 00:36:17.508
And at the 11th hour,

00:36:17.508 --> 00:36:19.670
President Nixon
vetoed the bill.

00:36:23.014 --> 00:36:25.683
Since the veto,
millions of families have gone

00:36:25.683 --> 00:36:28.452
without the kind of quality,
affordable care

00:36:28.452 --> 00:36:30.853
all young children need
to flourish.

00:36:37.728 --> 00:36:40.631
But one of America's
largest employers

00:36:40.631 --> 00:36:43.801
does receive federal funding
to provide high quality,

00:36:43.801 --> 00:36:47.171
affordable childcare
to its employees' families.

00:36:47.171 --> 00:36:51.842
It regards that care as
a top organizational priority.

00:36:51.842 --> 00:36:53.411
Man:
The most important thing to us

00:36:53.411 --> 00:36:57.048
is always that our families
are taken care of.

00:36:57.048 --> 00:36:59.417
If our families
are taken care of,

00:36:59.417 --> 00:37:01.052
there's a sense
of security out there

00:37:01.052 --> 00:37:02.186
that we don't have to worry
about them

00:37:02.186 --> 00:37:04.388
and we can concentrate
on the mission.

